{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778523460680,"sessionID":"ses_1e7c382eaffetRr2vNztTc7BFR","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"bash","callID":"chatcmpl-tool-852d85741cc340a4","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"command":"cat __issue_context__.json","description":"Read the full issue context file to avoid truncation"},"output":"{\n  \"body\": \"3 imported terms are unsatisfiable due violations of taxon constraints:\\nFMA:77600\\nZFA:0000497\\nZFA:0000592\\n\\nSolution proposed by @gouttegd in #3592 \\n\\nFor the first one (FMA:77600), I think the problematic axiom is\\n\\n'[epiphyseal tract](http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/UBERON_0034714)' EquivalentTo '[cranial neuron projection bundle](http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/UBERON_0034713)' and ([innervates](http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/RO_0002134) some '[parietal organ](http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/UBERON_0004869)')\\n\\nThat innervates bit seems too precise. The parietal organ is only a part of the '[pineal complex](http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/UBERON_0015238)' (a part that does not exist in mammals), but the '[pineal tract](http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/UBERON_0034715)' (a branching part of the epiphyseal tract) innervates another part of the pineal complex, the '[pineal body](http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/UBERON_0001905)'.\\n\\nSo if a branch of the epiphyseal tract innervates a distinct part of the pineal complex, then the entire epiphyseal tract clearly innervates more than just the parietal organ.\\n\\nI believe the axiom should be\\n\\n'[epiphyseal tract](http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/UBERON_0034714)' EquivalentTo '[cranial neuron projection bundle](http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/UBERON_0034713)' and ([innervates](http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/RO_0002134) some '[pineal complex](http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/UBERON_0015238)')\\n\\nAs for the other two (the ZFA ones), I think the problem lies with the '[adductor muscle of hip](http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/UBERON_0011144)'.\\n\\nThat term is logically defined as\\n\\n'[adductor muscle of hip](http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/UBERON_0011144)' EquivalentTo '[adductor muscle](http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/UBERON_0011145)' and ('[part of](http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/BFO_0000050)' some '[pelvic complex](http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/UBERON_0010709)')\\n\\nbut is also explicitly classified as\\n\\n'[adductor muscle of hip](http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/UBERON_0011144)' SubClassOf '[innervated by](http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/RO_0002005)' some '[obturator nerve](http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/UBERON_0005465)'\\n\\nThis is an instance of a pattern that I call “loose definition, tight classification”, where a logically defined term has a “tight” classification that brings more constraints than what its “loose” definition allows – the problem being that the constraints of the tight classification will then apply to all the terms that fall under the loose definition.\\n\\nIn this instance, the logical definition of adductor muscle of hip makes it valid for all vertebrates (all species that have an '[appendage girdle complex](http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/UBERON_0010707)'), but its classification as being innervated by the obturator nerve makes it specific to tetrapods only. And thus the '[superficial pelvic adductor](http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/UBERON_2000592)', which is intended to apply to teleosts (and as such mapped to ZFA:0000592) becomes also specific to tetrapods, since it is inferred to be a adductor muscle of hip.\\n\\nSo, either:\\n\\n(A) adductor muscle of hip is intended to apply to tetrapods only, in which case it should not have a logical definition that extends to all vertebrates, or\\n\\n(B) adductor muscle of hip is intended to apply to all vertebrates, in which case it should not be said to be innervated by a tetrapod-specific nerve.\\n\\n\",\n  \"comments\": [],\n  \"title\": \"Revise lofical definition causing violations of taxon constraints\",\n  \"url\": \"https://github.com/obophenotype/uberon/issues/3596\"\n}\n","metadata":{"output":"{\n  \"body\": \"3 imported terms are unsatisfiable due violations of taxon constraints:\\nFMA:77600\\nZFA:0000497\\nZFA:0000592\\n\\nSolution proposed by @gouttegd in #3592 \\n\\nFor the first one (FMA:77600), I think the problematic axiom is\\n\\n'[epiphyseal tract](http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/UBERON_0034714)' EquivalentTo '[cranial neuron projection bundle](http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/UBERON_0034713)' and ([innervates](http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/RO_0002134) some '[parietal organ](http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/UBERON_0004869)')\\n\\nThat innervates bit seems too precise. The parietal organ is only a part of the '[pineal complex](http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/UBERON_0015238)' (a part that does not exist in mammals), but the '[pineal tract](http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/UBERON_0034715)' (a branching part of the epiphyseal tract) innervates another part of the pineal complex, the '[pineal body](http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/UBERON_0001905)'.\\n\\nSo if a branch of the epiphyseal tract innervates a distinct part of the pineal complex, then the entire epiphyseal tract clearly innervates more than just the parietal organ.\\n\\nI believe the axiom should be\\n\\n'[epiphyseal tract](http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/UBERON_0034714)' EquivalentTo '[cranial neuron projection bundle](http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/UBERON_0034713)' and ([innervates](http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/RO_0002134) some '[pineal complex](http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/UBERON_0015238)')\\n\\nAs for the other two (the ZFA ones), I think the problem lies with the '[adductor muscle of hip](http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/UBERON_0011144)'.\\n\\nThat term is logically defined as\\n\\n'[adductor muscle of hip](http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/UBERON_0011144)' EquivalentTo '[adductor muscle](http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/UBERON_0011145)' and ('[part of](http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/BFO_0000050)' some '[pelvic complex](http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/UBERON_0010709)')\\n\\nbut is also explicitly classified as\\n\\n'[adductor muscle of hip](http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/UBERON_0011144)' SubClassOf '[innervated by](http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/RO_0002005)' some '[obturator nerve](http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/UBERON_0005465)'\\n\\nThis is an instance of a pattern that I call “loose definition, tight classification”, where a logically defined term has a “tight” classification that brings more constraints than what its “loose” definition allows – the problem being that the constraints of the tight classification will then apply to all the terms that fall under the loose definition.\\n\\nIn this instance, the logical definition of adductor muscle of hip makes it valid for all vertebrates (all species that have an '[appendage girdle complex](http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/UBERON_0010707)'), but its classification as being innervated by the obturator nerve makes it specific to tetrapods only. And thus the '[superficial pelvic adductor](http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/UBERON_2000592)', which is intended to apply to teleosts (and as such mapped to ZFA:0000592) becomes also specific to tetrapods, since it is inferred to be a adductor muscle of hip.\\n\\nSo, either:\\n\\n(A) adductor muscle of hip is intended to apply to tetrapods only, in which case it should not have a logical definition that extends to all vertebrates, or\\n\\n(B) adductor muscle of hip is intended to apply to all vertebrates, in which case it should not be said to be innervated by a tetrapod-specific nerve.\\n\\n\",\n  \"comments\": [],\n  \"title\": \"Revise lofical definition causing violations of taxon constraints\",\n  \"url\": \"https://github.com/obophenotype/uberon/issues/3596\"\n}\n","exit":0,"description":"Read the full issue context file to avoid truncation","truncated":false},"title":"Read the full issue context file to avoid truncation","time":{"start":1778523460671,"end":1778523460677}},"id":"prt_e18424a0e001q6b6Ay8bCx6yP5","sessionID":"ses_1e7c382eaffetRr2vNztTc7BFR","messageID":"msg_e183dc5100018uoWeAFenXHoMz"}}
